    "body": "@kboshold @davidkna @andytom it's possible that I'm doing something wrong, but I'm seeing an issue with using the `cmd_duration` module in `starship_transient_rprompt_func` after trying out the 1.21.0 release.\r\n\r\nIt looks like the duration is \"off by one,\" such that the transient rprompt prints the duration of the previous command?\r\n\r\nRelevant starship config:\r\n\r\n```toml\r\n[cmd_duration]\r\nmin_time = 0\r\nformat = '[$duration](bold yellow) '\r\n\r\n[status]\r\ndisabled = false\r\nformat = '[\\[exit: $status\\]](red) '\r\n\r\n[character]\r\nformat = '[\\$ ](white)'\r\n\r\n[time]\r\nformat = '[($status_code$cmd_duration) at $time](yellow)'\r\nuse_12hr = true\r\ndisabled = false\r\n\r\n```\r\n\r\nFish startup config:\r\n\r\n```fish\r\nfunction starship_transient_prompt_func\r\n    starship module character\r\nend\r\n\r\nfunction starship_transient_rprompt_func\r\n    starship module $argv cmd_duration\r\n    starship module $argv status\r\n    starship module time\r\n    printf \" <-transient\"\r\nend\r\n\r\n\r\nstarship init fish | source\r\nenable_transience\r\n```\r\n\r\n<img width=\"650\" alt=\"image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/472a7631-7791-4c97-8280-11e06b8b53c6\">\r\n\r\n\r\nIf I understand things correctly, it's looks like the transient prompt is being generated before the command executes 🤔 \r\n\r\nAny ideas? I've tried in a new shell, etc. Thanks again for the new release. Appreciate any help here!\r\n",
